  "texts": [
    "This adaptability should also ensure that decisions made by LLMs are explainable, fostering trustworthy solutions.Therefore, it is imperative to design multi-modal LLMs endowed with sensing, grounding, and instructibility properties in an attempt to enable AI-native networks that can have alignment abilities as well as universal capabilities.Here, universal foundation model for wireless systems can be defined as AI models tailored to handle a wide array of tasks and applications within the wireless domain, irrespective of the network architecture and standards.",
    "Furthermore, they must demonstrate proficiency in understanding the real-world workings of the wireless environment behind the sensed data.",
    "This includes the ability to reason and provide conclusions for novel scenarios and generate novel information across diverse facets of wireless communication, covering areas such as network management, resource allocation, protocol adherence, and troubleshooting.",
    "B. ContributionsThe main contribution of this paper is the introduction of of grounded and instructible large multi-modal models (LMMs) that are universal and ensure that the AI-native wireless systems achieves alignment capabilities, as shown in Fig. 1.Our key contributions include:• We first propose a novel framework for universal, wireless-centric foundation models, that goes beyond [2]-[4] by integrating the following capabilities into LMMs: 1) Multi-modal data fusion: fusing multi-modal Intent LMM Grounding Observations Generated Actions (e.g., resource allocation, transmit signaling, task specific commands, etc.)",
    "Instructibility (environment feedback, neurosymbolic AI) Multi-Modal Sensing Extended Reality (XR) Autonomous Vehicle Robot Prompt (Network State) Explanation Planning Action Evaluation Memory Line-of-sight (LoS) LMM Stages Online Framework Offline Framework Training of Causal LMM (causal reasoning, RAG) sensing information to a shared semantic space thus enabling efficient training of universal foundation models, 2) Grounding: involving the creation of a wirelessspecific language through RAG [7] and leveraging causal reasoning, and 3) Instructibility: facilitating transparent interactions between the wireless environment and LMMs through online reinforcement learning (RL) and interactive prompting and neuro-symbolic AI to perform logical and mathematical reasoning."
  ],
